      <trans-unit id="10981" identifier="59ced97ef8757b49683caaf57e6207bd">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;ct-abstraction&quot; title=&quot;Abstraction&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns10981:0crwdne10981:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[5]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10982" identifier="7a3f474f96b41f8444cfc0a314a5578c">
        <source>Each of the cards in this activity represents a bit inside a digital device.</source>
        <target>crwdns10982:0crwdne10982:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[6]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10983" identifier="9d20744e367c89913788a5ddd92009f3">
        <source>When we arrange all of our ‘bits’ together in the square this is a
representation of some data (admittedly random data in the magic trick, but it
could be done with real data!).</source>
        <target>crwdns10983:0crwdne10983:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[6]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10984" identifier="3d325e93c1911dae18114a872fda1222">
        <source>This means our grid is an abstraction because it is a model that could be used
to represent any piece of data that can be stored on a digital device, for
example a sound file, a video, or even a piece of code!</source>
        <target>crwdns10984:0crwdne10984:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[6]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10985" identifier="7ca1cce9bc789f9d38045770108363e7">
        <source>Examples of what you could look for:</source>
        <target>crwdns10985:0crwdne10985:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 4&#13;
XPath: /h4[2]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10986" identifier="eb8d243e8a6840733a99b5543f464b33">
        <source>Are students able to explain that each card is a bit and that the cards can
represent data?
Can they see the connection between the grid of cards and a piece of data made
up of bytes?</source>
        <target>crwdns10986:0crwdne10986:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[7]</note>
      </trans-unit>
