      <trans-unit id="11004" identifier="1048ee5c08ce80660a5ea18e0ae59002">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;ct-evaluation&quot; title=&quot;Evaluation&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11004:0crwdne11004:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[17]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11005" identifier="31684139916271ca1ec5e3a04340b092">
        <source>The parity trick is always able to detect and correct errors if one bit has
been flipped, but it is important to evaluate this algorithm for different
kinds of errors as well.</source>
        <target>crwdns11005:0crwdne11005:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[18]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11006" identifier="ccd172044d8dc3ca98ef777ace08f9fe">
        <source>If more than one card is flipped (i.e. more than one error occurs) then we can
tell something is wrong with the data, but our algorithm can’t tell us how to
fix this!</source>
        <target>crwdns11006:0crwdne11006:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[18]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11007" identifier="68b8d8189ddd0b2d9f49dffffb21f7f4">
        <source>Even worse, if more than two bits are flipped then sometimes we might not even
be able to detect the error!</source>
        <target>crwdns11007:0crwdne11007:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[18]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11008" identifier="4c40c0f04f93d5cb71c81a1785bd6603">
        <source>It’s important that we evaluate this algorithm, because if it is going to fail
sometimes we need to know.</source>
        <target>crwdns11008:0crwdne11008:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[18]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11009" identifier="2f66803f3637d8576b9e2b56deec92e0">
        <source>Computer Scientists evaluate algorithms like these and improve them when they
find problems with them.</source>
        <target>crwdns11009:0crwdne11009:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[18]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11010" identifier="ee945efc504e5ccf8a3f1c6b2bc14938">
        <source>Examples of what you could look for:</source>
        <target>crwdns11010:0crwdne11010:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 4&#13;
XPath: /h4[5]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11011" identifier="54fad2ce16ee9a8032c8815557c53ec1">
        <source>Ask students “What kind of errors can be detected and corrected with the
parity cards?
At what point can you only detect but not correct and error?
Why is that?”</source>
        <target>crwdns11011:0crwdne11011:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[19]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11012" identifier="54aba59e77a086a066cd181155cbcdd6">
        <source>Can students explain what goes wrong when we try to detect the error if two
cards are flipped?</source>
        <target>crwdns11012:0crwdne11012:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[20]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11013" identifier="3e36fd398241fc175b47e35cddcdc6f1">
        <source>{panel end}</source>
        <target>crwdns11013:0{panel end}crwdne11013:0</target>
