XPath: /p[21]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11014" identifier="7f1b0f3b3177e2fc5aa8ccdf994c3388">
        <source>{panel type=&quot;ct-logic&quot; title=&quot;Logic&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns11014:0crwdne11014:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[22]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11015" identifier="0dd746299c5de4e6b9c02b8efbc0e81d">
        <source>Flipping a card will always change a row/column from odd to even, no matter
what the card is in what the other cards in the row/column are.</source>
        <target>crwdns11015:0crwdne11015:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[23]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11016" identifier="b3d3349b25d5e9bbbe1df28aab8d29ff">
        <source>Also, the idea that the corner card is correct for both the new row and column
is an advanced concept, but a pattern that some students might recognise.</source>
        <target>crwdns11016:0crwdne11016:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[24]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11017" identifier="d2663645150b5be5b55859ada486fd3c">
        <source>Examples of what you could look for:</source>
        <target>crwdns11017:0crwdne11017:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 4&#13;
XPath: /h4[6]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11018" identifier="8f198de114bc54ddeba1ca44d9521a1e">
        <source>Can students explain why a single card flip always changes the number of black
cards to an odd number?</source>
        <target>crwdns11018:0crwdne11018:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[25]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="11019" identifier="7762bf9a12720e477affb33239ac75c9">
        <source>Can students explain why the corner card will be correct for both the row and
column?
(This involves fairly advanced reasoning).</source>
        <target>crwdns11019:0crwdne11019:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
